President Muhammadu Buhari and Netherlands Prime Minister Mark Rutte Tuesday met in Abuja to discuss bilateral relations and agreed on ways to continue to work together to improve bilateral trade volumes as well as private sector investments.  A communiqu√© issued at the end of the meeting said the two leaders reviewed the progress that has been made with implementing the Memorandum of Understanding on deepening the bilateral relations between the two nations concluded and signed by the respective Foreign Ministers in The Hague in July 2018.  Addressing State House Correspondents after the meeting, Prime Minister Rutte noted that Netherlands is the 3rd largest trading partner with Nigeria as he pledged his country's continous support to Nigeria for an increase in agricultural productivity, and commitment towards eradicating human trafficking.  The Prime Minister also commended Nigeria for its enormous participation in the International Criminal Court in Hague towards promoting International law and the fight against insurgency and countering violent extremism. He stated that Netherlands is poised to help Nigeria and regional West Africa countries on the Lake Chad issue.  After the bilateral consultations between delegations of both countries, President Buhari and Prime Minister Rutte witnessed the signing of the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on dairy chain development signed by Governor Abubakar Sani Bello of Niger State and Mr Ben Langat, Managing Director, FrieslandCampina WAMCO Plc.  Our State House Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the agreement on dairy chain development is expected to save Nigeria about 1.2 billion dollars from milk importation annually.